window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["ischemic-evaluation"]={"slug": "ischemic-evaluation", "title": "Noninvasive Ischemia Evaluation", "tagline": "Choosing, performing, and correctly reading every noninvasive ischemia test — from the treadmill ECG and the Duke score to PET flow reserve, TID, and FFR-CT — in the ISCHEMIA era.", "level": 2, "readMin": 38, "takeaways": ["Pretest probability and ECG interpretability drive test selection before any modality is ordered: an interpretable resting ECG in a patient who can exercise earns a plain treadmill test, while an uninterpretable ECG (LBBB, paced, pre-excitation, digoxin, >1 mm resting ST depression, LVH with strain) mandates imaging.", "The Duke treadmill score integrates exercise time, ST deviation, and angina into a validated prognostic number; a score at or below −11 predicts high annual mortality and should prompt anatomic evaluation, while a score at or above +5 is reassuring.", "Each imaging modality has a signature false read: the LBBB false-septal defect on exercise/dobutamine, breast and diaphragmatic attenuation artifact on SPECT, the subendocardial dark-rim artifact on stress CMR, and calcium blooming on coronary CTA. Knowing the artifact is how you avoid the catheterization it would otherwise trigger.", "Transient ischemic dilation (TID) and a drop in post-stress LVEF are high-risk markers of extensive, balanced, or left-main disease that can hide behind visually 'normal' relative perfusion images; PET myocardial flow reserve quantifies absolute flow and unmasks balanced ischemia.", "The dobutamine biphasic response (low-dose improvement then high-dose worsening) is the best noninvasive predictor of functional recovery after revascularization because it demonstrates both viability and jeopardy in the same segment.", "ISCHEMIA reframed the goal of testing: in stable patients with moderate-to-severe ischemia and preserved EF, imaging guides symptom management and identifies the anatomy (left main, high-risk multivessel, low EF) that changes prognosis — it does not by itself mandate revascularization."], "references": ["2021 AHA/ACC/ASE/CHEST/SAEM/SCCT/SCMR Guideline for the Evaluation and Diagnosis of Chest Pain", "2023 AHA/ACC/ACCP/ASPC/NLA/PCNA Guideline for the Management of Patients With Chronic Coronary Disease", "ISCHEMIA and ISCHEMIA-CKD Trials (New England Journal of Medicine, 2020)", "ISCHEMIA-EXTEND — Long-Term Follow-up of the ISCHEMIA Trial (2023)", "PROMISE Trial — Anatomic versus Functional Testing for Stable Chest Pain (New England Journal of Medicine, 2015)", "SCOT-HEART Trial — Coronary CT Angiography in Stable Chest Pain", "MR-INFORM Trial — Stress CMR Perfusion versus FFR-Guided Management", "FAME and FAME 2 Trials — Fractional Flow Reserve-Guided PCI (origin of the 0.80 ischemic threshold)", "PLATFORM and ADVANCE Studies — FFR-CT to Guide Referral for Invasive Angiography", "MESA — Coronary Artery Calcium Percentile Thresholds by Age, Sex, and Race", "Duke Treadmill Score (Mark and colleagues, original derivation and validation)", "ASNC/SNMMI Imaging Guidelines and Standards for SPECT and PET Myocardial Perfusion Imaging"], "guidelines": [{"society": "AHA/ACC Chest Pain", "year": "2021", "cor": "1", "loe": "B", "text": "In intermediate-risk patients with stable chest pain and no known CAD, coronary CT angiography or a stress imaging test (stress echo, SPECT/PET MPI, or stress CMR) is recommended for diagnosis and risk stratification; the choice depends on patient characteristics, local expertise, and whether an anatomic or functional answer is needed."}, {"society": "AHA/ACC Chest Pain", "year": "2021", "cor": "1", "loe": "B", "text": "For patients able to exercise with an interpretable resting ECG and no prior CAD, exercise treadmill ECG testing is a reasonable first-line functional test."}, {"society": "AHA/ACC Chest Pain", "year": "2021", "cor": "2a", "loe": "B", "text": "In patients with stable chest pain and known coronary stenosis of uncertain significance on CCTA, FFR-CT is reasonable to determine lesion-specific ischemia and guide the decision for invasive angiography."}, {"society": "ACC/AHA Prevention", "year": "2019", "cor": "2a", "loe": "B", "text": "In asymptomatic adults at intermediate risk in whom statin decisions are uncertain, coronary artery calcium scoring is reasonable to reclassify risk; a calcium score of zero favors withholding or deferring statin therapy in most, while a score of 100 or above, or at the 75th percentile or higher for age and sex, favors initiation."}, {"society": "AHA/ACC Chronic Coronary Disease", "year": "2023", "cor": "1", "loe": "A", "text": "In stable patients with moderate-to-severe ischemia and preserved ejection fraction, an initial strategy of optimized medical therapy is recommended, with revascularization reserved for lifestyle-limiting angina despite therapy or for high-risk anatomy, reflecting the ISCHEMIA results."}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 68-year-old woman with exertional chest pressure and a resting ECG showing a left bundle branch block is referred for ischemia evaluation. She can walk on a treadmill. Which testing strategy is most appropriate?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Exercise treadmill ECG with interpretation of ST-segment changes"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Exercise SPECT myocardial perfusion imaging"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Dobutamine stress echocardiography"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Vasodilator (regadenoson) SPECT or PET myocardial perfusion imaging"}, {"key": "E", "text": "No testing is needed; treat empirically"}], "correct": "D", "explanation": "With LBBB the resting ST segments are uninterpretable, so exercise ECG alone (A) is out. More importantly, in LBBB both exercise and dobutamine produce a rate-dependent false anteroseptal perfusion defect because septal diastolic filling and perfusion become asynchronous when heart rate rises, which would mimic LAD disease. Vasodilator stress (adenosine, dipyridamole, or regadenoson) increases flow without a large rise in heart rate and avoids this artifact, so vasodilator SPECT or PET is preferred. The same principle applies to ventricular-paced rhythms."}, {"stem": "A 59-year-old man undergoes exercise SPECT MPI. The relative perfusion images show only a small, mild reversible defect, but the stress LV cavity is visibly larger than the rest cavity with a TID ratio of 1.35, and the post-stress LVEF is 8 points lower than at rest. What does this picture most likely indicate?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A benign finding of no clinical consequence"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Extensive, likely balanced or multivessel/left-main ischemia despite modest relative defects"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Breast attenuation artifact"}, {"key": "D", "text": "A technically failed acquisition requiring repeat imaging"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Isolated microvascular disease with no epicardial stenosis"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Transient ischemic dilation and a fall in post-stress LVEF are high-risk markers. In balanced multivessel or left-main disease, global subendocardial hypoperfusion reduces counts everywhere, so the relative images can look deceptively normal or show only minor defects while the cavity dilates and function drops with stress. TID above roughly 1.2 plus post-stress stunning should prompt anatomic evaluation regardless of how modest the perfusion defect appears. PET with absolute flow quantification would show a globally reduced flow reserve."}, {"stem": "A 62-year-old obese man has a fixed perfusion defect in the inferior wall on SPECT. On the gated images, the inferior wall thickens and moves normally through the cardiac cycle. Which statement is correct?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "This is a completed inferior myocardial infarction (scar)"}, {"key": "B", "text": "This is most consistent with diaphragmatic attenuation artifact, not true scar"}, {"key": "C", "text": "This represents active inferior wall ischemia"}, {"key": "D", "text": "This indicates hibernating myocardium"}, {"key": "E", "text": "The study is nondiagnostic and cannot be interpreted"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Preserved wall motion and thickening on the gated images within a 'fixed' defect strongly argue for attenuation artifact rather than infarction, because scarred myocardium does not thicken normally. Inferior wall attenuation from the diaphragm is classic in men (breast attenuation causes anterior/anterolateral defects in women). Prone imaging, attenuation correction, or PET can confirm. True scar would show hypokinesis or akinesis with reduced thickening in the affected territory."}, {"stem": "During dobutamine stress echocardiography, a resting akinetic inferior segment begins to contract at 10 mcg/kg/min but becomes akinetic again at 40 mcg/kg/min. What does this biphasic response indicate?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Transmural scar with no viable myocardium"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Viable myocardium subtended by a significant stenosis, likely to recover function after revascularization"}, {"key": "C", "text": "A normal physiologic response"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Dynamic left ventricular outflow tract obstruction"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Non-jeopardized viable myocardium requiring no intervention"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "The biphasic response — improvement at low-dose dobutamine (contractile reserve, proving viability) followed by deterioration at higher doses (inducible ischemia, proving jeopardy) — is the best dobutamine echo predictor of functional recovery after revascularization. Sustained improvement without later worsening suggests viable but non-jeopardized myocardium; no change in an akinetic segment suggests scar; worsening without initial improvement suggests ischemia in already-thinned myocardium."}, {"stem": "A patient is scheduled for regadenoson SPECT. Which pre-test instruction most directly prevents a false-negative study?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Hold beta-blockers for 48 hours"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Avoid caffeine and methylxanthine-containing products for at least 12 hours before the study"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Take a full dose of aspirin the morning of the study"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Fast for 24 hours before the study"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Hold all antihypertensives the morning of the study"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Caffeine and other methylxanthines are competitive adenosine-receptor antagonists. If present, they blunt the coronary hyperemia produced by regadenoson (and adenosine and dipyridamole), reducing flow heterogeneity between normal and stenosed territories and producing a false-negative perfusion study. Patients must abstain from coffee, tea, chocolate, caffeinated sodas, and theophylline for at least 12 hours (aminophylline is in fact the antidote used to reverse regadenoson side effects). Beta-blockers blunt exercise and dobutamine tests, not vasodilator perfusion imaging."}, {"stem": "A 47-year-old man with atypical chest pain and a low-to-intermediate pretest probability has a normal ECG and normal troponin. Which testing approach best uses the strengths of the available modalities to exclude obstructive coronary disease?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Coronary CT angiography, which has a very high negative predictive value"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Immediate invasive coronary angiography"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Coronary artery calcium score alone to exclude obstructive disease"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Dobutamine stress echocardiography"}, {"key": "E", "text": "No testing and discharge without follow-up"}], "correct": "A", "explanation": "In younger patients with low-to-intermediate pretest probability, coronary CTA is an excellent gatekeeper because its negative predictive value approaches 99%; a normal CCTA essentially excludes obstructive CAD, consistent with PROMISE and SCOT-HEART. Invasive angiography (B) is inappropriate as a first test at this risk level. A calcium score of zero lowers risk but does not exclude non-calcified obstructive plaque, so CAC alone (C) is insufficient in a symptomatic patient. Functional testing is reasonable but CCTA's anatomic exclusion is the most efficient way to rule out disease here."}, {"stem": "A 55-year-old man completes 7 minutes of a standard Bruce protocol, develops 1 mm of horizontal ST-segment depression, and reports no chest pain during the test. Using the Duke treadmill score, how is he best classified?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Score of −13, high risk, refer for anatomic evaluation"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Score of +2, intermediate risk"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Score of +7, low risk"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Score of −8, high risk"}, {"key": "E", "text": "The score cannot be calculated without knowing the peak heart rate"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Duke treadmill score = exercise time − (5 × ST deviation in mm) − (4 × angina index). Here that is 7 − (5 × 1) − (4 × 0) = +2, which falls in the intermediate band (−10 to +4). Peak heart rate is not a term in the score, so E is wrong. A score of +5 or higher would be low risk and −11 or lower high risk; +2 warrants clinical judgment and often further evaluation if symptoms persist."}, {"stem": "A 58-year-old woman has persistent exertional angina. Coronary CTA shows no obstructive stenosis. Cardiac PET shows no regional perfusion defect, but the global myocardial flow reserve is 1.4. Which diagnosis does this pattern best support?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Balanced three-vessel obstructive disease"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Coronary microvascular dysfunction (INOCA)"}, {"key": "C", "text": "A technically failed PET acquisition"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Transmural inferior scar"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Normal study; angina is noncardiac"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "A globally reduced myocardial flow reserve (normal >2.0; here 1.4) with no regional defect and angiographically normal epicardial arteries is the signature of coronary microvascular dysfunction, a mechanism of ischemia with non-obstructive coronary arteries (INOCA). Balanced three-vessel disease (A) is excluded by the normal CCTA. Because MFR is an absolute rather than relative measurement, PET can flag this abnormal physiology that relative SPECT counts would report as normal."}, {"stem": "On a first-pass stress perfusion CMR, a thin dark line along the subendocardium appears only on the single frame of peak left ventricular contrast enhancement, disappears on the following frames, spans less than one pixel in width, does not follow a coronary territory, and has no corresponding late gadolinium enhancement. What is the most likely explanation?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A true subendocardial perfusion defect requiring catheterization"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Subendocardial dark-rim (Gibbs) artifact"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Circumferential subendocardial infarction"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Microvascular obstruction (no-reflow)"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Diffuse myocardial edema"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "The dark-rim artifact is transient, thin, appears at the moment of peak contrast, and ignores coronary anatomy. A true perfusion defect persists across several dynamic frames, is wider than a single pixel, conforms to a coronary territory, and frequently pairs with late gadolinium enhancement or a wall-motion abnormality. The described findings are classic for the Gibbs (truncation) artifact and should not trigger catheterization."}], "sections": [{"id": "learning-objectives", "title": "Learning Objectives", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "This module takes the internal medicine resident to first-year cardiology fellow depth on noninvasive ischemia testing. The goal is not to memorize a menu of tests but to reason like a consultant: match the test to the patient, know exactly how each study is acquired and read, and recognize the specific scenarios where each modality is misread so you avoid the unnecessary catheterization a false read would trigger."}, {"type": "list", "label": "You should be able to", "items": ["Select a first test from pretest probability, ability to exercise, and resting ECG interpretability, and state which resting ECGs make exercise ST analysis uninterpretable.", "Calculate and risk-stratify with the Duke treadmill score and list the high-risk exercise responses that outweigh a low score.", "Contrast exercise and dobutamine stress echocardiography and interpret the biphasic response for viability.", "Distinguish reversible from fixed defects on SPECT, recognize breast and diaphragmatic attenuation artifact, and explain the significance of transient ischemic dilation and balanced ischemia.", "Explain what PET adds through absolute myocardial blood flow and flow reserve, and when stress CMR and its dark-rim artifact matter.", "Position coronary CTA, calcium scoring, and FFR-CT in the diagnostic pathway and prescribe the pharmacologic stress agents correctly.", "Apply ISCHEMIA and appropriate-use principles so testing changes management rather than reflexively driving revascularization."]}]}, {"id": "framework", "title": "The Selection Framework: Match the Test to the Patient", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Every ischemia evaluation begins with three questions before any modality is chosen. What is the pretest probability of obstructive coronary disease? Can the patient exercise to an adequate workload? Is the resting ECG interpretable for ST-segment changes? The answers, not habit or local availability, should drive the order."}, {"type": "p", "text": "Testing has two currencies. Functional tests (exercise ECG, stress echo, SPECT, PET, stress CMR) ask whether a stenosis limits flow or provokes ischemia. Anatomic tests (coronary CTA, calcium scoring) ask what the arteries actually look like. A young patient with atypical symptoms and low-to-intermediate probability is best served by an anatomic test that can exclude disease with high negative predictive value. A patient with known coronary disease and new symptoms is usually better served by a functional test that localizes and quantifies ischemia."}, {"type": "defs", "label": "The ischemic cascade (why perfusion changes before symptoms)", "entries": [{"term": "Sequence of events", "def": "With increasing flow limitation, perfusion heterogeneity appears first, then diastolic dysfunction, then systolic wall-motion abnormality, then ST-segment change on the ECG, and finally angina. Perfusion imaging detects ischemia earlier in the cascade than wall-motion imaging, which detects it earlier than the ECG."}, {"term": "Practical consequence", "def": "This ordering is why perfusion techniques (SPECT, PET, CMR) are more sensitive for milder single-vessel disease, while wall-motion techniques (stress echo) are highly specific but detect ischemia slightly later in the cascade."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Exercise is itself diagnostic and prognostic information. Whenever a patient can exercise to an adequate workload, an exercise-based test is preferred over a pharmacologic one because functional capacity, the blood-pressure and heart-rate response, symptom reproduction, and recovery all carry prognostic weight that a pharmacologic study discards.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "table", "label": "First-test logic at a glance", "head": ["Patient situation", "Preferred first test", "Why"], "rows": [["Can exercise, interpretable resting ECG, no known CAD", "Exercise treadmill ECG", "Cheapest, adds functional capacity and Duke score; imaging reserved for abnormal or indeterminate results"], ["Cannot exercise, or needs imaging localization", "Pharmacologic stress imaging (MPI, echo, or CMR)", "Vasodilator or dobutamine substitutes for exercise; imaging localizes territory"], ["Uninterpretable resting ECG (LBBB, paced, WPW, digoxin, >1 mm ST depression, LVH strain)", "Stress imaging (vasodilator MPI preferred for LBBB/paced)", "ST analysis is invalid; imaging bypasses the ECG limitation"], ["Young, low-to-intermediate probability, need to exclude CAD", "Coronary CTA", "Very high negative predictive value rules out obstructive disease"], ["Known stenosis of uncertain significance on CCTA", "FFR-CT or downstream functional test", "Determines lesion-specific ischemia before catheterization"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The consultant question is never 'is there ischemia' in the abstract; it is 'will the result of this test change what I do.' If a positive and a negative result both lead to the same management, the appropriate-use answer is often to defer testing. This is the discipline the appropriate-use criteria and the ISCHEMIA trial were written to enforce.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "exercise-ecg", "title": "Exercise Treadmill ECG and the Duke Score", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The exercise treadmill test is the oldest and least expensive ischemia study. The patient walks a graded protocol (Bruce is standard) while the ECG, heart rate, blood pressure, and symptoms are monitored. A positive ischemic response is at least 1 mm (0.1 mV) of horizontal or downsloping ST-segment depression measured 80 ms after the J point. Upsloping depression is less specific. The test is considered adequate only when the patient reaches at least 85% of the age-predicted maximum heart rate (approximated as 220 minus age), unless it is stopped earlier for ischemia or limiting symptoms."}, {"type": "p", "text": "The exercise ECG has modest sensitivity and specificity for obstructive disease and performs best when applied to intermediate pretest probability, where a result can meaningfully move the post-test probability. Specificity falls in populations prone to false-positive ST depression (women, LVH, digoxin), which is one reason the interpretation should never rest on the ST answer alone."}, {"type": "p", "text": "The single most useful output is not the yes/no ST answer but the Duke treadmill score, which folds exercise capacity, ST change, and angina into one validated prognostic number."}, {"type": "defs", "label": "Duke treadmill score (DTS)", "entries": [{"term": "Formula", "def": "DTS = exercise time in minutes (Bruce protocol) − (5 × maximum ST deviation in mm) − (4 × angina index). The angina index is 0 for no angina, 1 for non-limiting angina, and 2 for exercise-limiting angina."}, {"term": "Risk bands", "def": "A score of +5 or higher is low risk, with roughly 0.25% annual cardiovascular mortality. A score of −10 to +4 is intermediate. A score of −11 or lower is high risk, with roughly 5% or greater annual mortality, and warrants anatomic evaluation."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "label": "Mnemonic", "text": "Duke = 'Time minus Five-ST minus Four-Angina.' The two multipliers ride down in order (5 then 4) as you move from ST deviation to angina. Remember that exercise time helps you and ischemia markers hurt you, so a fit patient with minimal ST change scores high (good) and a deconditioned patient with early ST depression and angina scores deeply negative (bad)."}, {"type": "list", "label": "High-risk exercise responses that override a reassuring ST answer", "items": ["ST-segment depression of 2 mm or more, especially at a low workload (under 5 METs) or persisting well into recovery", "Exercise-induced ST elevation in a non-infarct territory (suggests transmural ischemia or spasm)", "A fall in systolic blood pressure below baseline with exercise (exertional hypotension), signaling severe disease or LV dysfunction", "Poor functional capacity (under 5 METs) or chronotropic incompetence", "Sustained ventricular tachycardia or prolonged ST recovery time"], "depth": 2}, {"type": "list", "label": "Absolute contraindications to exercise testing", "items": ["Acute myocardial infarction within 2 days", "High-risk unstable angina not yet stabilized", "Uncontrolled arrhythmia with hemodynamic compromise", "Symptomatic severe aortic stenosis", "Decompensated heart failure, acute pulmonary embolism, acute aortic dissection, or acute myo/pericarditis"], "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "The exercise ECG is uninterpretable for ischemia when the baseline ST segments are already abnormal or the depolarization sequence is altered: left bundle branch block, ventricular-paced rhythm, ventricular pre-excitation (WPW), digoxin effect, resting ST depression greater than 1 mm, and LVH with a strain pattern. Ordering a plain treadmill ECG in these patients produces an answer you cannot trust. Move to imaging."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "In LBBB and ventricular pacing, do not simply switch to any imaging stressor. Both exercise and dobutamine raise heart rate and generate a rate-dependent false anteroseptal perfusion defect because septal filling and perfusion are asynchronous in LBBB. Vasodilator stress (adenosine, dipyridamole, regadenoson) increases flow with minimal heart-rate rise and is the correct stressor for these patients.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Review LBBB, ventricular-paced rhythm, and WPW morphology so you can recognize an uninterpretable resting ECG at a glance before ordering a treadmill test.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "ECG library: LBBB, paced, and pre-excitation patterns"}]}, {"id": "stress-echo", "title": "Stress Echocardiography", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Stress echocardiography detects ischemia as a new or worsening regional wall-motion abnormality that appears when oxygen demand exceeds supply. Baseline images are compared side by side with peak-stress images. A normal segment thickens and moves inward more vigorously with stress; an ischemic segment develops new hypokinesis, akinesis, or dyskinesis. It uses no radiation and adds direct assessment of valves, chamber size, and diastolic function."}, {"type": "table", "label": "Exercise versus dobutamine stress echo", "head": ["Feature", "Exercise stress echo", "Dobutamine stress echo"], "rows": [["Preferred when", "Patient can exercise adequately", "Patient cannot exercise"], ["Stressor", "Treadmill or supine/upright bicycle", "Graded dobutamine infusion, atropine added to reach target HR"], ["Added prognostic data", "Functional capacity, BP and symptom response", "Assesses viability and contractile reserve"], ["Key limitation", "Post-treadmill imaging must be captured within ~60–90 s before recovery", "Requires monitoring for arrhythmia and dynamic LVOT obstruction"]]}, {"type": "defs", "label": "Dobutamine protocol and responses", "entries": [{"term": "Infusion", "def": "Dobutamine is escalated in 3-minute stages, typically 5, 10, 20, 30, then 40 mcg/kg/min; atropine 0.5 mg increments (to about 1–2 mg total) are added if the target heart rate is not reached. Dobutamine is a beta-1 agonist that raises heart rate, contractility, and myocardial oxygen demand."}, {"term": "Normal", "def": "Hyperdynamic augmentation of all segments with rising dose."}, {"term": "Ischemia", "def": "A normally contracting segment develops new hypokinesis/akinesis at higher doses."}, {"term": "Biphasic response", "def": "A resting dysfunctional segment improves at low dose (contractile reserve, proving viability) then worsens at high dose (proving inducible ischemia). This is the best predictor of functional recovery after revascularization."}, {"term": "Sustained improvement", "def": "Improves and stays improved without later worsening — viable, non-jeopardized myocardium."}, {"term": "No change (scar)", "def": "An akinetic segment that never improves is transmural scar and will not recover."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "label": "Mnemonic", "text": "Read the biphasic curve as 'up then down = viable and in danger.' Only a segment that first wakes up (viability) and then fails (ischemia) both needs and will benefit from revascularization. A segment that only wakes up is safe; a segment that never wakes up is dead.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "list", "label": "Dobutamine stress echo cautions", "items": ["Avoid in significant ventricular arrhythmia, uncontrolled hypertension (over ~180/110), recent MI or unstable angina, aortic dissection, and large aortic aneurysm.", "Dobutamine can provoke dynamic LVOT obstruction and hypotension, particularly in hypertrophied or hyperdynamic ventricles and in hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.", "Side effects include arrhythmia, chest pain, and supraventricular tachycardia; effects are reversed with a short-acting beta-blocker such as esmolol."], "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The chief weakness of stress echo is image quality and reader dependence. Poor acoustic windows (obesity, lung disease) degrade endocardial definition; ultrasound-enhancing contrast agents rescue many of these studies by opacifying the LV cavity and defining the endocardial border. A hypertensive response can also blunt augmentation and cause a false-positive apical abnormality; always record the peak blood pressure when reading.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Reference normal apical and parasternal wall-motion so you can recognize a new regional wall-motion abnormality on stress.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: echocardiographic wall-motion references"}]}, {"id": "spect", "title": "SPECT Myocardial Perfusion Imaging", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT) maps relative myocardial perfusion using a technetium-99m agent (sestamibi or tetrofosmin) or thallium-201. Tracer is injected at peak stress and again at rest, and the two sets of images are compared by coronary territory. The central distinction is reversibility."}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/spect-mpi-lateral-ischemia.jpg", "alt": "Stress and rest SPECT myocardial perfusion showing a reversible lateral defect", "caption": "Stress/rest SPECT MPI: arrows mark a reversible lateral-wall defect — reduced tracer on stress that fills in at rest, the signature of inducible ischemia.", "credit": "Sincefalastrum — CC BY-SA 4.0, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Isquemia_lateral.jpg"}, {"type": "defs", "label": "Reading SPECT defects", "entries": [{"term": "Reversible defect", "def": "Reduced tracer uptake on stress that normalizes at rest = inducible ischemia in that territory."}, {"term": "Fixed defect", "def": "Reduced uptake on both stress and rest = infarcted scar, or attenuation artifact if wall motion is preserved."}, {"term": "Territory mapping", "def": "Anterior/anteroseptal/apical = LAD; inferior/inferoseptal = RCA (or dominant circumflex); lateral = left circumflex."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Attenuation artifact is the most common SPECT false read. Breast tissue attenuates the anterior and anterolateral walls (classically in women); the diaphragm attenuates the inferior wall (classically in men). Both mimic a fixed defect. The disambiguator is the gated wall-motion data: if the 'fixed defect' segment thickens and moves normally, it is attenuation, not scar, because true scar does not thicken. Confirm with attenuation correction, prone imaging (for the inferior wall), or PET."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "label": "Mnemonic", "text": "'Motion beats a defect.' On any fixed SPECT defect, look at the gated cine first. Normal thickening in the defect means artifact; absent thickening means real scar. Wall motion is the tie-breaker the perfusion images alone cannot give you."}, {"type": "defs", "label": "Transient ischemic dilation (TID) and balanced ischemia", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "TID", "def": "The LV cavity appears larger on the post-stress images than at rest, with a TID ratio above roughly 1.2 (exact threshold depends on protocol and software). It reflects diffuse subendocardial hypoperfusion and apical stunning that make the cavity look dilated. TID is a high-risk marker of severe, extensive, or left-main/multivessel disease even when the perfusion defects themselves look modest."}, {"term": "Balanced ischemia / left-main pattern", "def": "SPECT compares counts relative to the brightest myocardium. When all territories are hypoperfused together (three-vessel or left-main disease), no single region stands out and the relative images can look falsely normal. The clues to look past this trap are TID, a post-stress drop in LVEF (stunning), increased lung uptake (thallium), an abnormally low stress LVEF, and multiple reversible defects."}]}, {"type": "list", "label": "High-risk SPECT findings that mandate anatomic evaluation", "items": ["Large or multiple reversible defects across more than one coronary territory", "Transient ischemic dilation of the LV cavity", "A drop in LVEF from rest to post-stress (post-stress stunning) or a low stress LVEF", "Increased lung uptake with thallium imaging (marker of stress-induced LV dysfunction)"], "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Radiation and count statistics matter. Technetium agents give better image quality and lower radiation than thallium and permit gating for wall motion and EF. When ordering, remember that a normal high-quality SPECT confers a low annual event rate (under ~1%), so the study's power is as much in its reassuring negative as in its positive.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Review examples of reversible versus fixed perfusion defects, attenuation artifact, and transient ischemic dilation on labeled perfusion images.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: myocardial perfusion imaging examples"}]}, {"id": "pet", "title": "PET Perfusion and Myocardial Flow Reserve", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Positron emission tomography uses rubidium-82 or nitrogen-13 ammonia to image perfusion with higher spatial resolution, routine attenuation correction, and lower radiation than SPECT. Its defining advantage is quantification: PET measures absolute myocardial blood flow at rest and at stress and computes the myocardial flow reserve (MFR), the ratio of stress to rest flow."}, {"type": "defs", "label": "Myocardial flow reserve (MFR)", "entries": [{"term": "Definition", "def": "MFR = maximal hyperemic myocardial blood flow divided by resting flow. A normal global MFR is above 2.0; values under about 1.5 are associated with high cardiovascular risk."}, {"term": "Why it solves balanced ischemia", "def": "Because MFR is an absolute measurement, not a relative one, it detects the globally reduced flow of three-vessel or left-main disease that relative SPECT counts can miss. A uniformly low MFR across all territories flags balanced ischemia that would otherwise read as 'normal.'"}, {"term": "Microvascular disease", "def": "A reduced global MFR with normal epicardial arteries and no regional defect points to coronary microvascular dysfunction (a mechanism of INOCA, ischemia with non-obstructive coronary arteries)."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "PET is the preferred perfusion test in patients where SPECT struggles: the obese, women with breast attenuation, and anyone in whom balanced ischemia is a concern. Its attenuation correction and absolute flow make the images both cleaner and more quantitative.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "PET perfusion is almost always vasodilator-based because the short half-lives of rubidium-82 (about 76 seconds) and N-13 ammonia (about 10 minutes) require imaging during pharmacologic hyperemia rather than after treadmill exercise. PET also enables viability assessment with F-18 FDG, where a perfusion-metabolism mismatch (reduced perfusion but preserved FDG uptake) identifies hibernating, recoverable myocardium, whereas a matched perfusion-metabolism defect indicates scar.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "cmr", "title": "Stress Cardiac MRI", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Stress cardiovascular magnetic resonance combines several answers in one study without ionizing radiation: vasodilator first-pass perfusion for ischemia, cine imaging for wall motion and function, late gadolinium enhancement for infarct and viability, and tissue characterization for edema and infiltration. Dobutamine CMR is an alternative that assesses inducible wall-motion abnormalities when vasodilators are contraindicated."}, {"type": "list", "label": "What stress CMR does well", "items": ["High spatial resolution detection of subendocardial perfusion defects", "Late gadolinium enhancement quantifies infarct transmurality; less than 50% transmural enhancement predicts functional recovery after revascularization", "Combines ischemia, function, and viability in a single session with no radiation"]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "The classic stress CMR false read is the subendocardial dark-rim (Gibbs) artifact, which mimics a real perfusion defect. Distinguish them: a true perfusion defect persists across several dynamic frames, is wider (more than one pixel), follows a coronary territory, and often shows corresponding late gadolinium enhancement or wall-motion change. A dark-rim artifact is transient, thin, appears at the moment of peak contrast, and does not respect coronary anatomy.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "MR-INFORM showed CMR perfusion-guided management was non-inferior to invasive FFR-guided management for major cardiac events with fewer revascularizations, which established stress CMR as a first-line functional test rather than a niche one. Practical limits: many but not all modern CIEDs are MRI-conditional, severe claustrophobia limits some patients, and gadolinium is avoided in severe renal impairment; newer macrocyclic agents carry lower nephrogenic systemic fibrosis risk.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Review first-pass perfusion CMR and late gadolinium enhancement patterns, including the subendocardial dark-rim artifact.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: stress perfusion CMR and LGE"}]}, {"id": "ccta-cac", "title": "Coronary CTA and Calcium Scoring", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Coronary CT angiography (CCTA) is the leading anatomic test. It images the coronary lumen and wall after iodinated contrast and, in the right patient, essentially excludes obstructive disease because its negative predictive value approaches 99%. The PROMISE and SCOT-HEART trials established CCTA as at least equivalent to functional testing for stable chest pain, with SCOT-HEART showing a lower rate of coronary death or nonfatal myocardial infarction at 5 years, driven largely by intensified preventive therapy after plaque was seen."}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/ccta-3d.jpg", "alt": "3D volume-rendered coronary CT angiography", "caption": "3D volume-rendered coronary CTA: the epicardial coronaries traced over the heart surface — the anatomic strength of CCTA for ruling out obstructive disease.", "credit": "CC BY 4.0, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coronary_CT_Angiography_Scan.jpg"}, {"type": "figure", "depth": 1, "src": "../assets/fig/coronary-calcium-score.png", "alt": "Coronary artery calcium Agatston score report", "caption": "A coronary artery calcium (Agatston) report: non-contrast CT quantifies calcified plaque per vessel (here an LAD lesion, magenta), refining risk in stable patients.", "credit": "MBq — CC BY-SA 4.0, via Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:CCTA_Agatston-Score.png"}, {"type": "table", "label": "CCTA and calcium scoring compared", "head": ["Feature", "Coronary CTA", "Coronary artery calcium (CAC) score"], "rows": [["Contrast", "Iodinated contrast, ECG-gated", "Non-contrast, gated"], ["Best use", "Symptomatic low-to-intermediate probability; exclude obstructive CAD", "Asymptomatic intermediate-risk primary prevention; refine statin decisions"], ["Output", "Stenosis severity, plaque type, CAD-RADS category", "Agatston score quantifying calcified plaque burden"], ["Key strength", "Very high negative predictive value; visualizes non-calcified plaque", "'Power of zero' — a score of 0 confers very low near-term risk"], ["Key limit", "Heavy calcium blooming and motion overestimate stenosis", "Does not detect soft/non-calcified plaque or luminal stenosis directly"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "CCTA prep is part of the read. Achieve a heart rate under about 60 with beta-blockade and give sublingual nitroglycerin to dilate the coronaries; a fast or irregular rate and unopened arteries are the main causes of nondiagnostic scans. A patient who cannot breath-hold or has severe contrast allergy or advanced renal impairment is a poor CCTA candidate.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Dense coronary calcium causes blooming that overestimates stenosis severity and can force a false-positive read toward catheterization. In a heavily calcified vessel, a functional test or FFR-CT often serves the patient better than trusting the CCTA stenosis estimate. Conversely, remember a calcium score of zero does not exclude non-calcified obstructive plaque in a symptomatic patient.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Use the CAC score as a decision modifier, not a symptom test. In asymptomatic intermediate-risk adults, a score of 0 supports deferring statin in most, while a score of 100 or above, or at the 75th percentile for age and sex, supports initiation, consistent with MESA-derived thresholds. It is not appropriate for acute chest pain, where luminal stenosis and non-calcified plaque are the concern.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "ffr-ct", "title": "FFR-CT: Adding Physiology to Anatomy", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "FFR-CT applies computational fluid dynamics to a standard coronary CTA dataset to estimate the fractional flow reserve of a given lesion without additional imaging, contrast, or medication. It answers the question CCTA alone cannot: is this anatomic stenosis actually flow-limiting."}, {"type": "defs", "label": "Interpreting FFR-CT", "entries": [{"term": "Threshold", "def": "An FFR-CT value of 0.80 or below indicates a hemodynamically significant, ischemia-producing lesion — the same cutoff validated for invasive FFR in the FAME and FAME 2 trials."}, {"term": "Best application", "def": "Intermediate stenoses (roughly 40–90%) seen on CCTA, where the anatomic severity is ambiguous. The PLATFORM and ADVANCE studies showed FFR-CT reduces referrals to invasive angiography that turns out to show no obstructive disease."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "The natural workflow is CCTA first, then FFR-CT on any intermediate lesion, so a single non-invasive study delivers both the anatomy and its physiologic significance and the catheterization lab is reserved for lesions likely to need treatment.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "FFR-CT inherits the weaknesses of its parent scan. Heavy calcification, motion, misregistration, and poor opacification degrade the model and can produce unreliable values, so image quality gating is essential before trusting an FFR-CT number. It estimates hyperemic physiology computationally rather than measuring it, which is a strength for workflow and a caution for edge cases.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "pharmacologic-agents", "title": "Pharmacologic Stress Agents", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "When a patient cannot exercise, or when the modality (PET, most CMR) requires it, pharmacologic stress substitutes. There are two mechanisms. Vasodilators (adenosine, dipyridamole, regadenoson) produce coronary hyperemia so that stenosed territories receive relatively less flow, creating the perfusion heterogeneity that imaging detects. Dobutamine instead raises heart rate and contractility to increase demand and provoke wall-motion ischemia."}, {"type": "table", "label": "Pharmacologic stress agents: dosing, cautions, monitoring", "head": ["Agent", "Mechanism", "Dose", "Key contraindications", "Major side effects", "Monitoring / reversal"], "rows": [["Regadenoson", "Selective A2A adenosine agonist → coronary hyperemia", "0.4 mg IV fixed bolus over ~10 s, saline flush; tracer 10–20 s later", "High-grade AV block or sinus node dysfunction without pacemaker; SBP under 90; caution in active bronchospasm", "Dyspnea, flushing, chest discomfort, headache, GI upset, transient AV block", "Continuous ECG/BP; reverse with aminophylline; hold caffeine/methylxanthines 12 h"], ["Adenosine", "Non-selective adenosine receptor agonist → hyperemia", "140 mcg/kg/min IV over 6 min (tracer at 3 min)", "High-grade AV block/sinus node disease, bronchospastic disease, SBP under 90, recent caffeine", "Flushing, chest pain, dyspnea, AV block, bronchospasm", "Ultra-short half-life (seconds); stop infusion to reverse; aminophylline if needed"], ["Dipyridamole", "Blocks adenosine reuptake → raises endogenous adenosine", "0.56 mg/kg IV over 4 min", "Same as adenosine; longer-acting so effects persist", "Prolonged flushing, headache, chest pain, AV block, bronchospasm", "Continuous ECG/BP; reverse with aminophylline"], ["Dobutamine", "Beta-1 agonist → raises HR, contractility, demand", "5→10→20→30→40 mcg/kg/min, 3-min stages; add atropine 0.5 mg to target HR", "Significant arrhythmia, uncontrolled HTN, recent MI/unstable angina, aortic dissection/aneurysm, dynamic LVOT obstruction/HOCM", "Arrhythmia, chest pain, hypotension from dynamic LVOT obstruction, palpitations", "Continuous ECG/BP; reverse with short-acting beta-blocker (esmolol)"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Caffeine and methylxanthines block adenosine receptors and blunt vasodilator hyperemia, producing a false-negative perfusion study. Patients must abstain from coffee, tea, chocolate, caffeinated soft drinks, and theophylline for at least 12 hours before any adenosine, dipyridamole, or regadenoson study. Note the irony that aminophylline, a methylxanthine, is precisely the antidote used to reverse vasodilator side effects."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "label": "Mnemonic", "text": "'Vasodilators for the wheezer's heart, dobutamine when the airway's tight.' Adenosine and dipyridamole can trigger bronchospasm, so in reactive airway disease favor dobutamine (or use regadenoson cautiously, as it is more A2A-selective and better tolerated in COPD). Conversely, when arrhythmia or LVOT obstruction is the worry, favor a vasodilator over dobutamine.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Withhold antianginal beta-blockers before an exercise or dobutamine study when the goal is to provoke ischemia, because rate control blunts the heart-rate response and lowers sensitivity. Beta-blockers do not blunt vasodilator perfusion imaging, so they need not be held for adenosine/regadenoson MPI. Match the hold list to the stressor, not to habit.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "misreads", "title": "How Each Test Is Misread and How to Avoid It", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "A consultant is defined less by ordering the right test than by not being fooled by the wrong answer it sometimes gives. Each modality has a signature failure mode, and each has a specific defense."}, {"type": "table", "label": "Signature false reads and their fixes", "head": ["Modality", "Classic misread", "How to avoid it"], "rows": [["Exercise ECG", "False-positive ST depression (women, digoxin, LVH, resting ST changes); uninterpretable in LBBB/paced/WPW", "Screen the resting ECG first; move to imaging when baseline ST is abnormal; weigh the Duke score and functional capacity, not ST alone"], ["Stress echo", "False-positive apical abnormality with hypertensive response; missed ischemia from poor windows", "Record peak BP; use ultrasound-enhancing contrast for endocardial definition; compare peak, not recovery, images"], ["SPECT", "Attenuation artifact read as fixed scar; balanced ischemia read as normal", "Check gated wall motion (motion beats a defect); use attenuation correction/prone imaging; look for TID, post-stress EF drop, lung uptake"], ["PET", "Motion/misregistration degrading absolute flow; extravasated tracer", "Verify registration; trust global MFR to unmask balanced disease that relative images hide"], ["Stress CMR", "Subendocardial dark-rim artifact mimicking a perfusion defect", "Real defect persists across frames, is wider, follows a territory, and pairs with LGE or wall-motion change"], ["Coronary CTA", "Calcium blooming overestimating stenosis; motion artifact", "Control heart rate and give nitroglycerin; use FFR-CT or a functional test for heavily calcified vessels"], ["Calcium score", "Reassuring 0 misapplied to a symptomatic patient", "Use CAC only for asymptomatic risk refinement; a symptomatic patient needs CCTA or functional testing"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Two structural biases cut across all functional testing. Referral bias inflates apparent sensitivity because patients with positive tests go to catheterization and confirm disease, while negatives are not verified. And the relative-count problem of SPECT means diffuse disease can look normal. Both push you to read the ancillary high-risk markers (TID, EF response, functional capacity) rather than the headline perfusion or ST result in isolation.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "ischemia-auc", "title": "ISCHEMIA, Appropriate Use, and Putting It Together", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The purpose of ischemia testing changed with the ISCHEMIA trial. Stable patients with moderate-to-severe ischemia on stress testing were randomized to an initial invasive strategy or optimized medical therapy. The trial deliberately excluded left main disease (screened out by blinded coronary CTA in most participants), ejection fraction below 35%, recent acute coronary syndromes, and advanced renal disease. Over a median of about 3.2 years there was no reduction in the primary composite of cardiovascular death, myocardial infarction, resuscitated arrest, or hospitalization for unstable angina or heart failure with the invasive approach. Revascularization improved angina and quality of life. ISCHEMIA-CKD showed no benefit of the invasive strategy in advanced kidney disease."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "The clinical translation: the magnitude of ischemia on a stress test does not by itself mandate revascularization in stable disease. Test to guide symptom management and to find the anatomy that still changes prognosis — left main and high-risk multivessel disease and severely reduced EF — which ISCHEMIA deliberately excluded and which remain revascularization indications.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "In extended follow-up (ISCHEMIA-EXTEND, reported in 2023) over a median of roughly 5.7 years, all-cause mortality remained no different between strategies; the invasive arm showed a lower cardiovascular mortality that was offset by higher non-cardiovascular mortality. The durable message is unchanged: an initial conservative strategy is reasonable for stable moderate-to-severe ischemia with preserved EF and no left-main disease.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "steps", "label": "A practical pathway for stable suspected ischemia", "items": ["Characterize symptoms and estimate pretest probability; address alternative diagnoses when probability is very low.", "Check whether the patient can exercise and whether the resting ECG is interpretable.", "Interpretable ECG and able to exercise: exercise treadmill ECG; escalate to imaging only if abnormal or indeterminate.", "Uninterpretable ECG or unable to exercise: choose a stress imaging test, using vasodilator MPI for LBBB or paced rhythm.", "Low-to-intermediate probability where exclusion is the goal: coronary CTA, adding FFR-CT for intermediate lesions.", "Optimize medical therapy first; reserve invasive angiography for refractory angina, high-risk noninvasive findings (large ischemic burden, TID, post-stress EF drop), or suspected left-main/multivessel disease."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Appropriate-use is the discipline of ordering only tests whose result will change management. Repeat testing of an asymptomatic patient with stable known disease, or testing before low-risk noncardiac surgery in a functionally capable patient, are the common low-value orders. The best consultants document, before ordering, the specific management fork each possible result would open.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Read the primary ISCHEMIA and PROMISE trial reports for the evidence behind functional versus anatomic testing and the conservative-versus-invasive strategy.", "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/", "label": "PubMed: ISCHEMIA and PROMISE trials"}]}]};
